The graphene Raman signal was mapped across the flake and surrounding substrate, Fig. 2d,e. The G, D and 2D peaks are all suppressed over the Bi2Se3 flake without any change in the peak ratio or peak positions. This indicates that the Raman suppression is not a result of damage to the graphene layer, strain or other changes to the layer structure29. Instead, this is consistent with a charge transfer process, affecting exciton lifetime at the heterostructure interface. Such transfer processes have been observed in graphene/Bi2Se3 heterostructures, even with an interfacial BiO2 layer13. Without this oxide layer, electron-hole separation due to interfacial band-bending is expected to have significant effects on exciton dynamics, since there is a Fermi level mismatch of 0.8 eV at the interface30. The high D peak intensity and drop in \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
